<HEADLINE>
<P>
STAGE; BROOKS TAKS 'PAUL ROBESON' BEYOND SCRIPT'S BOUNDARIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON SHIRLEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 He laughs, cries, sings, dances, preaches, mugs, testifies.  
</P>
<P>
 He plays dozens of characters in one night. Avery Brooks does about everything 
an actor has ever wanted to do in "Paul Robeson," his star turn at the Westwood 
Playhouse. 
</P>
<P>
 While he does it all very well, Brooks is as remarkable for his stamina as for 
anything else. 
</P>
<P>
 This is a performance that goes on for nearly 2 hours, 45 minutes, and Brooks 
has done it hundreds of times, including a stint at the Westwood two years ago. 
But his attention to each moment never lapses. Nor does his big, booming voice. 
</P>
<P>
 The vehicle he drives, Phillip Hayes Dean's script, is nothing to shout about. 
The tone is largely reverential, seldom introspective, and mostly structured as 
a succession of dozens of anecdotes.  
</P>
<P>
 Because of the limits of the genre, Brooks frequently finds himself forced to 
awkwardly repeat the comments of the people with whom Robeson is conversing. 
</P>
<P>
 Anyone who wants an accurate picture of the real Robeson would be better off 
reading a biography. Dean used his dramatic license frequently to create more 
of a show.  
</P>
<P>
 For example, one whole sequence has Robeson experiencing epiphanies in Africa 
and on the voyage back to America, but the real Robeson never traveled in 
sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
<P>
 Brooks is masterfully accompanied at the piano, and occasionally in spoken 
dialogues, by Ernie Scott.  
</P>
<P>
 In fact, the dramatic highlight of the evening is the familiar dialogue (it 
has been used in other plays as well) between Robeson and a congressional 
interrogator played by Scott. This exchange is so fiery that one wishes the 
whole play were less of a monodrama. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, for the most part Brooks' showmanship -- and the thought that this may 
indeed inspire someone to read more about the legendary entertainer and 
activist -- justifies the show. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Paul Robeson," Westwood Playhouse, 10886 LeConte Ave., West L.A. 
Fridays-Saturdays, 8 p.m.; Sundays, 3 p.m. No performances Feb. 11-13. Ends 
Feb. 27. $30-$37.50. (310) 208-5454. Running time: 2 hours, 45 minutes. * 
</P>
<P>
 Avery Brooks: Paul Robeson 
</P>
<P>
 Ernie Scott: Lawrence Brown 
</P>
<P>
 Phillip Hayes Dean's play, produced by Eric Krebs in association with William 
Ross. Directed by Harold Scott. Musical direction and arrangements by Ernie 
Scott. Special arrangements and orchestration by Eva C. Brooks. Lighting by 
Shirley Prendergast.  
</P>
<P>
 Original choreography Dianne McIntyre. DON SHIRLEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
