<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAGUAR GEARING UP TO LEASE USED CARS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Still trying to persuade would-be Jaguar owners that they can trust as well as 
love the cars, the British luxury car maker plans to begin widespread leasing 
of used models within a year. 
</P>
<P>
 A reputation for poor quality and oft-told tales of frequent breakdowns has 
been hard to shake. 
</P>
<P>
 But Jaguar's quality rankings are improving rapidly under the tutelage of Ford 
Motor Co., which bought the company for $2.5 billion in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
 Michael Dale, president of Jaguar North America, said that when the current 
crop of leased Jaguars returns beginning late this year, a used-leasing program 
should be in place. He refused to estimate the likely monthly payment on a used 
lease but said it would be hundreds of dollars less than the $579 monthly 
payment on a new lease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
