<HEADLINE>
<P>
CULTURE WATCH; ARE '60S ACTIVISTS HAPPY AT LAST? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KATHLEEN DOHENY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 How are middle-aged '60s activists faring? 
</P>
<P>
 Female former activists are happier and more successful than non-activist 
women or male former activists, according to a study in the Journal of 
Personality and Social Psychology by Williams College and Boston University. 
</P>
<P>
 The study included 116 people -- 46 of them activists -- who came of age in 
the mid-1960s. They were interviewed at ages 31 and 41: 
</P>
<P>
 * Male former activists had lower-paying jobs, often in public service, than 
non-activist men or female activists. They were the least happy. 
</P>
<P>
 * Female activists protested for the rights of everyone -- women, blacks, the 
poor, draft resisters. Men often took on a personal cause against the Vietnam 
War draft. 
</P>
<P>
 * Both fought traditional wife/mother and soldier/provider roles. But society 
changed more to accept women in the workplace than to accept non-traditional 
men. KATHLEEN DOHENY 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020794-0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 011335 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 7, 1994, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part E; Page 3; Column 2; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
161 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
RELAXATION TECHNIQUES FOR THE SHUTTER-SHY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EMILY ADAMS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 So you hate to be photographed?  
</P>
<P>
 Here are a few tips from professional photographers on how you can get over 
your fears and see better results on film. 
</P>
<P>
 * Loosen up before the first shot is taken. Do anything you can to keep from 
going rigid: rub your arms, rub your face. Take deep breaths and blow out 
vigorously. 
</P>
<P>
 * Ignore the camera. If you can, make it invisible and relate to the 
photographer, not the box. 
</P>
<P>
 * Do not practice your smile beforehand. A practiced smile is a phony smile. 
The camera can see the difference. 
</P>
<P>
 * Allow the photographer -- amateur or no -- to take a lot of pictures. This 
way, the best ones can be chosen and the rest can be trashed. 
</P>
<P>
 * If it's a long photo session, insist on getting up and moving around. Shake 
your limbs. 
</P>
<P>
 * Change body position, even if only slightly: drop your shoulder, move you 
legs. 
</P>
<P>
 * Convince yourself that this is fun. You can do that, the same way you 
convinced yourself you look bad. EMILY ADAMS 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020794-0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 011336 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
